# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chinese-jump-rope
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Games in which a ball is hit or thrown have been referenced as far back as Homer and ancient Egypt.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] A game similar to handball was played by Northern and Central Americans from 1500 BC, most famously by the Aztecs as the Mesoamerican ballgame, but no references to a rebound game using a wall survive.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] It is thought that these ancient games more closely resembled a form of hand tennis.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Further examples of similar games include the European-originated games of *Basque pelota* (or *Jai-alai*), Gaelic handball, *Valencian frontó*, International fronton and Eton fives.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] References to similar games (then referred to as either "hand-tennis" and "hand-ball") have been found as early as 1287, when the Synod of Exeter banned the game due to the damage it caused to church buildings.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Other notable examples of wall ball games being banned include Robert Braybrooke, Bishop of London, who in 1385 prohibited the game.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Another recorded game of striking a ball against a wall using a hand was in Scotland in 1427, when King James I ordered a cellar window in his palace courtyard to be blocked up, as it was interfering with his game.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] In Ireland, the earliest written record of a similar game is in the 1527 town statutes of Galway, which forbade the playing of ball games against the walls of the town.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The first depiction of an Irish form of handball does not appear until 1785.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The sport of handball in Ireland was eventually standardized as Gaelic handball.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] By the mid-19th century, Australians were playing a similar game, which developed into the modern sport of Australian handball.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] In *Treacherous Beauty*, by Mark Jacob and Stephen H.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Case, about the Arnold-Andre conspiracy, Major John André and General Sir Henry Clinton are said to have played a game called handball during the American Revolution.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The earliest record of the modern game in the United States mentions two handball courts in San Francisco in 1873.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The sport grew over the next few decades.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] By the early 1900s, four-wall handball was well established and a one-wall game was developed in New York City by beach-goers who hit bald tennis balls with their hands against the sides of the wooden jetties that lined beaches.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] This led to a rise in one-wall handball at New York beaches and by the 1930s, thousands of indoor and outdoor one-wall courts had been built throughout the city.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] American handball is seen predominantly in parks, beaches, and high school yards in New York City, Lynbrook, New York, Philadelphia, Chicago and other large urban areas.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] National championships in handball have been held annually in the United States since 1919.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] These championships were organized by the Amateur Athletic Union (AAU) until 1950, when their control was transferred to the newly formed United States Handball Association (USHA).
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] For a complete list of champions, see List of American Handball Champions in the United States, and List of American Handball Women's Champions in the United States.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The sports of racquetball, squash, fives, four-wall and one-wall paddleball were heavily influenced by handball.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Four-wall and one-wall paddleball were created when people took up wooden paddles to play on handball courts.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Four-wall paddleball was invented in 1930 by Earl Riskey, a physical-education instructor at the University of Michigan, when he came up with the idea of using paddles to play on the school's handball courts.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Racquetball was invented in 1949 by Joseph Sobek in Greenwich, Connecticut, when he played handball using a strung racquet.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] American handball is played on a walled court, with either a single (front) wall, three walls, or in a fully enclosed four-wall court; four-wall courts typically have a ceiling while three-wall courts may or may not.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The four-wall court is a rectangular box.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The front wall is 20 feet (6.1 m) square, and the side walls are 40 feet (12.2 m) long and 20 feet (6.1 m) high.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] In the middle of the floor lies a short line, dividing the floor into two 20 feet (6.1 m) squares.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Also along the floor is the service line, which is 5 feet (1.5 m) in front of the short line.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The service zone is the area between these two lines.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The back wall of the court is usually 12 feet (3.7 m) high, with an above gallery for the referee, scorekeeper and spectators.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Some courts have a glass back wall and glass side walls to allow for better viewing.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] In three-wall court handball, the court often has a front wall and two full side walls, or the front wall is flanked by two triangular wings.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Handball may be played as singles (two players against each other), doubles (two teams of two players), or "cutthroat" (three players rotating one against two).
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] In cutthroat handball, one server plays against two receivers, until they are "put out" (other terms include "down" or "side out").
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Serves rotate in this way until one player wins by scoring either 7, 11, 15, or 21 points.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Should both teams reach a score 1 below the winning score, the game can be continued by "win-by-two" or "straight".
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] In "win-by-two", the winning score is increased by 2 points.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] In 'straight', the score remains the same and cannot be pushed.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] When a tie of 20 is reached in a 21-point match, a common decision is 'straight 25', where the winning score is set to 25 and cannot be changed.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The cutthroat mode of play is also known as "triangles".
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The ball is served by one player standing in the service zone.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The server begins by dropping the ball to the floor of the service zone and striking it, after one bounce, with the hand or fist so that it hits the front wall.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The ball must hit the front wall first and it may then hit at most one side wall before the first bounce.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The served ball must then bounce on the floor past the short line but before reaching the back wall.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] If the served ball lands in front of the short line, it is called a "short", while a serve that reaches the back wall without bouncing is called "long", and a serve that hits both side walls before hitting the floor is called a "3-wall".
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] These are all types of errors known as service faults.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] After one service fault, the server will have only one serve remaining.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The server is "put out" by hitting two faults in a row and becomes the receiver, but if any serve hits the ceiling, floor, or a side wall *before* hitting the front wall, the server is out (no second serve allowed).
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] In doubles, the server's teammate has to stand in the service area with their back to a side wall in a service box, marked by a parallel line 18 inches (46 cm) from the side wall, until the ball passes the short line.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] While the server has the ball, the receiver must stand at least 5 feet (1.5 m) behind the short line, indicated by dashed lines extending 6 inches (15 cm) from each side wall.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Once the ball is served, the receiver must hit the ball either directly ("on the fly") or after the first bounce.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] A receiver choosing to take the serve on the fly, however, must first wait for the ball to cross the short line (the dashed line, in racquetball).
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The ball can bounce off the floor twice.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Also, any player during a return may hit the ball off the floor before it touches the front wall.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The server then hits the ball on the rebound from the front wall, and play continues with the opponents alternately hitting the ball until one of them fails to make a legal return.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] After the serve and return, the ball may be played from anywhere and may hit any number of walls, the ceiling, or a player so long as it hits the front wall before bouncing on the floor.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Players can "hinder" (block) their opponents from hitting the ball.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Servers failing to make a legal return is "put out" and becomes the receiver.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] If the receiver fails to make the return, a point goes to the server, who continues to serve until "put out".
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Only the server/serving team can score points.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The game goes to the player/team first to score 21 points.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] A match goes to the player/team to win two out of three games; the third game goes to 11 points.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] A three-wall handball court is an outside court with a front-wall, two side-walls (these may be "full" or "half"—half being a pair of sloping side-walls), and no back-wall in the play area.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] It is played very much like an indoor four-wall court, only with the challenge of returning the ball without any back-wall rebound.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The long line at the forty-foot mark is considered out if the ball hits it when hitting the floor.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] One-wall handball courts have a wall 20 feet (6.1 m) wide and 16 feet (4.9 m) high.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The court floor is 20 feet (6.1 m) wide and 34 feet (10.4 m) long.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] When not played as part of tournament or league play, the one-wall game typically uses the bigger ball called "the big blue".
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The main difference between one-wall handball and other versions is that the ball must always be played off the front wall.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] One-wall handball can be watched by more people than a four-wall game.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The court is also cheaper to build, making this version of handball popular at gymnasiums and playgrounds.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] In New York City alone, an estimated 2,299 public handball courts occupy the five boroughs.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] A typical outfit includes protective gloves, sneakers, athletic shorts and goggles.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Eye protection is required in tournament handball, as the ball moves at high speeds and in close proximity to the players.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] It is rarely used in "street" handball, however, where a softer "big blue" ball is usually used.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The black or blue rubber ball weighs 2.3 ounces (65 g) and is 1.875 inches (4.76 cm) in diameter (smaller, heavier, and more dense than a racquetball), is hit with a gloved hand (open palm, fingers, fist, back of hand) (informal games often do not include gloves).
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] A true handball is referred to as an "ace ball" or, in earlier days, "blackball".
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] A racquetball used to play handball is called a "big ball" or "big blue".
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] A small ball is hard, bounces higher and moves faster.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Types of small balls include the Red Ace (for men) and the White Ace (for women).
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] The Red Ace small ball is heavier than the White Ace small ball.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] A big ball bounces slower and is softer and hollower than a small ball.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Four-wall games use the small ball almost exclusively.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Three-wall and one-wall games use both balls.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/american-handball] Both balls are used extensively in New York City, with formal tournaments for big ball, one example being NYC Big Blue.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/ante-over] There are two teams, one on each side of the barrier.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/ante-over] A player on the team that starts with the ball throws the ball over the barrier to the other team, yelling some version of "Ante Over" to warn them that it has been thrown.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/ante-over] If the other team fails to catch the ball before it hits the ground, then they will yell "Ante Over" and throw it back.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/ante-over] If the team that is thrown to catches the ball, then the player holding the ball and this team run around the building and attempt to hit one of the members of the opposing team with the ball.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/ante-over] Players are "safe" if they succeed in running around the building without being hit.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/ante-over] If a player is hit, they then join the team of the player who hit them with the ball.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/ante-over] Play continues until one team has all of the players or just one is left.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/ante-over] In some versions of the game, if the ball bounces off the wall or rolls back without going over the roof, the thrower will yell "Pigs tail", to let the other team know the ball has been thrown but did not go over.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/ante-over] They then yell "Ante Over" again and make another attempt to throw the ball over the roof.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/ante-over] An indoor version of the game uses a curtain instead of a building.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/ante-over] Any tall obstacle that obscures the other team works for the game, although a gabled roof is part of traditional play.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/ante-over] When a building is used instead of a fence or some other narrow object, in some variations the ball must touch the other side of the roof.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/ante-over] Having the ball bounce this way can make it tougher for the other side to catch.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/ante-over] Some players even learn to finesse the ball rolling it up and over the roof.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/ante-over] When the barrier is a fence, or a similar obstacle that can be seen through, it is more difficult for the players to cheat as the other side can see if the ball does or does not hit the ground.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/ante-over] When it is a building, or other opaque barrier, players can sometimes stealth to the other side, catching the other team by surprise.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/ante-over] One rule has it that the opposing player can only be hit below the waist as a safety precaution like in dodge ball.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/ante-over] In some versions, players only have to run to the other side of the building to be "safe", while other versions require them to run all the way around the building.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] The national governed body of the sport is the "Atya Patya Federation of India".
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] The ministry of Youth Affairs and Sports, government of India, lists the federation amongst its list of recognised federation for the year 2013.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] The federation is headquartered in Nagpur.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] The first south Asian Atya patya Championship was held in Bhutan in June, 2013.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] Some of the alternative names for atya-patya are Killithattu/Klithatu (in Tamil Nadu), Kili Thadthu (in Sri Lanka), Wanjh Wati (in Sindh), Gallery, Sur-pati, Lon-pati, Darya-banth, saragari, saramani, tilli, uppinat, uppupatti, choupal pati, panchwati, and chikka.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] A related Bengali game is Dari Bandha/Dariabandha, in which the attacking team is considered to be "stealing salt" by making it up the court and then "taking the salt back" to the start of the court.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] In Southeast Asia, similar games can be found, such as Galah Panjang/Toi/Tui/Belon Acah in Malaysia, Gobak Sodor/Galah Asin in Indonesia, Htote See Toe in Myanmar, and Patintero in the Philippines.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] Due to the history of Dutch colonialism in the region, the game was also played by Dutch children.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] Atya-patya was mentioned in the Natṟiṇai, which was written before 300 AD.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] It was used as combat practice by soldiers in the Chola dynasty.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] The playing field is a rectangular court, with a central lane or "trench" 89 feet and 1 inch (27.15 m) long marked lengthwise down the middle of the court.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] Nine additional trenches, each 23 feet and 1 inch (7.03 m) long, are drawn on the court perpendicular to the central trench and 11 feet (3.4 m) away from each other, from one end of the court to the other.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] The game is played in four innings (turns), with each inning lasting for seven minutes, and the teams alternating attacking and defending roles in each inning.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] Before each inning, the defensive team places one player in each of the trenches.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] A batch of four players on the attacking team, who are referred to as "assailants", line up at one end of the court, in the area in front of the front trench.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] The goal of the assailants is to score by crossing each trench without being eliminated; the total number of points scored in an inning by the attacking team is equal to the number of trenches crossed by their furthest-advancing assailant.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] If an assailant is touched by a defender (and the defender commits no faults, such as stepping out of their trench, or lifting a foot at or immediately after the time of tagging the assailant), then the assailant is "out", and must leave the court.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] The assailant is also out if they step out of the field while failing to keep any part of their body grounded within the field.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] If an assailant crosses all nine trenches, they may say the word "Tond", which compels the defenders to turn around, allowing the assailant to now attempt to re-cross the nine trenches in the opposite direction.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] Atya-patya matches are decided on a best-of-three basis.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] The defender in the front trench is known as a "grenadier" or "sur", and is able to run in either the front trench or the central trench.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] Grenadiers are allowed to commit any fault other than a foot fault or hand fault where part of their body goes outside of their trench.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] Special rules apply when two or more assailants are encircled by a regular defender and a grenadier, which is known as a "ring".
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] The national level Atya Patya tournament for 2013 was held at Bhatkal in Karnataka.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] Represented by 22 states & Union Territories, the event was organized jointly by Karnataka Atya Patya association Davangere and Bhatkal Atya Patya association.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] The president of Puducherry Atya patya Association, Selvan refuted accusations levelled by Anbhagan, Member of Legislative Assembly, Puducherry, that Atya patya certificates were issued to take benefit of quota available to sports persons, in seats at medical colleges.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/atya-patya] He stated that the sport was registered in 22 states of India including in Tamil Nadu.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] It was suggested by James Redding Ware that the term was based on a blackface doll, itself inspired by a low-life character named "Black Sal," which appeared in an 1821 novel entitled *Life in London* by Pierce Egan, a contemporary of Charles Dickens.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] The game dates back to the 17th century, although the name "Aunt Sally" may have been a later addition.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] It was traditionally played in central English pubs and fairgrounds.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] An Aunt Sally was originally the modelled head of an old woman with a clay pipe in her mouth; the object was for players to throw sticks at the head in order to break the pipe.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] The target has also been a puppet, live person, or a simple ball on a stick.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] There are also other theories of how the game started.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] One such theory is that a live cockerel was placed on the stick, and people would throw sticks at it.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] Whoever killed it won the game and took home the chicken.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] Another theory is that in Port Meadow in Oxfordshire, at the time of the English Civil War, the Cavaliers (soldiers loyal to King Charles I) were bored and formed a game with sticks and makeshift materials similar to the game as understood today.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] The game has also been played outside of the UK; picnic attendees were reported to play Aunt Sally in Australia in the 1880s.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] Today, the game of Aunt Sally is still played as a pub game in Berkshire, Buckinghamshire, Gloucestershire, Oxfordshire, Northamptonshire and Warwickshire.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] In 2011 the inaugural Aunt Sally Singles World Championship took place at the Charlbury Beer Festival in Charlbury, West Oxfordshire.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] Among the attendees was Prime Minister David Cameron.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] The tournament has continued there annually ever since.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] On 24 August 2019, the first world championship for Aunt Sally pairs was held in the Bull, Launton, Oxfordshire, and was won by the pub team from The Bell, Bicester.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] Darren Moore and Billy Craig were the winners.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] Runners-up were Aimee Sheehan and Christopher Hulme.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] The game bears some resemblance to a coconut shy or skittles but with teams.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] Each team consists of eight players or five players depending on the local league.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] The ball is on a short plinth about 4 to 6 inches (100 to 150 mm) high by 3 inches (75 mm) diameter, known as the "dolly", which is placed on a dog-legged metal spike (the swivel) about 30 to 40 inches (750 mm to 1000 mm) high.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] Players throw sticks or short battens, about 18 by 2 inches (450 x 50 mm) at the dolly, from ten yards away, trying to knock it off without hitting the spike.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] Successfully hitting the dolly off is known as a "doll"; however, if the spike is hit first, then the score does not count and is called an "iron".
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] A zero score (after 6 sticks are thrown) is known as a "blob" and marked with an X on the scoreboard.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/aunt-sally] If all legs are a blob the person is a "blobber".
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] Australian handball is a ball sport played in an enclosed court in which players strike a small ball directly against a front wall using their hands rather than a racquet.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] Unlike similar court sports such as squash, no racket or other equipment is used; the ball is struck with the palm or fist.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] Play begins with a serve, in which the ball is hit directly against the front wall without first bouncing on the ground.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] The opposing player must return the ball before it bounces twice.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] During play, the ball may also rebound from side walls either before or after striking the front wall; however, after a player strikes the ball, it must contact the front wall before touching the ground.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] The game can be played in singles or doubles formats on courts with one, three, or four walls.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] The three-wall court is the most common configuration used for organized play.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] Courts used for the sport are found at a number of educational institutions and sporting facilities in Australia, including several private schools and colleges.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] Although its formal beginnings in Australia date from 1923, it has been played in some capacity or another since the 19th century.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] The first Australian Handball court was built by Melbourne hotel-keeper, Michael Lynch, in 1847.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] Its early development has been attributed to the work of Christian Brothers' Colleges.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] Handball was very strongly promoted among the students at Christian Brothers' Colleges, driven by the Brothers' view that handball "affords an excellent preparatory training for football, as it calls into play all the resources of the physical man".
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] Over most of its history, its primary play has been in Victoria, South Australia, and New South Wales.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] By 1970, there were about 1,000 players registered within the New South Wales, Victorian, and South Australian state associations.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] For many decades, the Australian Handball Council has held almost annual national championships, and each state has held its own state titles.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] During the 1950s and 1960s, both the Australian Singles Schoolboys Handball Championships and the Australian Doubles Schoolboys Handball Championships were held on a regular basis.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] Many great champions participated in these schoolboy rivalries.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] Additionally, over many decades Australians have made regular appearances at the World Junior and World Senior Titles.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] Within Australia, of more recent decades, the chief rivalries have been between Victoria and South Australia.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] For the past three decades, the states have generally competed at a 'midpoint' venue, often Warrnambool, Victoria, over one weekend annually, for the national handball championships.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] In some areas, modern changes to school venues have meant the disappearance of the school's traditional handball courts, making it harder on handballers to access the game.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] The game is nationally run by the Australian Handball Council, formed in 1928, of which the current executive director is Jim Kiley, and the Secretary/Treasurer is Greg Hay.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/australian-handball] A few highly respected names in the game's history include multiple national champions Jim Flattery, Tim Tucker, and George Macris in the first half of the 20th century, and John Hughes of Victoria, Paul Fallon of NSW , Lou Ravesi of SA, and Vic DeLuzio and Geoff Walsh of Victoria, in the 2nd half.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] Backyard cricket has connections to the pastimes of Australian, South African and New Zealand and English children who frequently lived on properties with large backyards, providing the facility to play this informal game of sport often with friends, family and neighbors.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] In South Asia, backyard cricket is very popular.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] Though loosely based upon the game of cricket, many aspects are improvised: the playing ground, the rules, the teams, and the equipment.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] Quite often there are no teams at all; the players take turns at batting and there is often no emphasis on actually scoring runs.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] Games with relatively few players typically forgo the teams and innings format of professional cricket, opting instead for a batters-vs-everyone format.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] Garden/backyard cricket in South Africa and Australia is considered by many to be the pinnacle event of social and sporting excellence in the summer period.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] Many games are paired with a barbecue which often has a carnival atmosphere.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] It is historically very popular on Australia Day.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] As a generally informal contest, the rules are flexible but usually agreed upon by the players prior to playing it.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] Below are listed some of the most common rules.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] Backyard cricket allows for rules to be changed, and the rules being played by will depend on the context and physical environment of the game, and the traditions and experience of the players.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] If the game is not played individually, the person who owns the bat and ball may choose to bat first.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] Play on an actual beach can be achieved either by using the flat strip of hard-packed sand along the surf line as the pitch, or by only "bowling" gentle full tosses to avoid the problem of the ball not bouncing off loose sand.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] If there are no true stumps available, then a bin, deckchair, boogie board or cool box may be used.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] Tennis balls are often used in place of cricket balls as they float in the water and don't get bogged in the sand as easily.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] In beach cricket the creases and the boundary are normally drawn in the sand in a line which extends well past the side of the agreed pitch to prevent them becoming obliterated in the first over.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] The batters will frequently redraw the line.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] Sometimes, play is shifted along the beach to a new pitch as the packed sand of the original pitch is turned up, thus reducing the standard of or even completely disabling bowling.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] The tide plays a big part in the standard of the pitch in beach cricket.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] During low tide, the pitch tends to be on the semi-wet sand, and is deemed superior than cricket played in high tide (when the pitch is on dryer, looser sand).
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] In particularly long matches, the play will shift up and down the beach depending on the tide.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] A major element of contemporary street cricket is the use of a tennis ball; in Pakistan, tennis balls began to be covered in tape in the late 20th century and turned into a "tape ball".
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] Tape ball cricket is played to the greatest extent in Pakistan, where it likely originated.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] Several street variants of cricket exist in Latin America, such as bete-ombro and plaquita.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] In nearby Suriname, there is a game called "bat-en-bal" which is likely derived from cricket; in bat-en-bal, one end of the pitch has a set of stumps.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] In March 2024, the first season of the Indian Street Premier League (ISPL) took place, which featured several elements of Indian street cricket such as the use of a tennis ball.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-cricket] The ISPL's goal is to prioritize the advancement of poorer cricket players and support the growth of tennis ball cricket.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-golf] The whereabouts of the game's origins remain unclear.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-golf] It is entirely probable that the game was "invented" many times in many locations as a fun game in the vein of horseshoes, shuffleboard, or croquet.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-golf] The game is very popular in Western Massachusetts where organized tournaments have occurred.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-golf] A relatively famous permanent course exists in Ludlow, Massachusetts on Chapin Street.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-golf] It is known as the Ancient Nine or Lavoie Course.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-golf] It is the only known course where the public is welcome to play the game on private property free of charge during daylight hours.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/backyard-golf] Another course exists in Willoughby, Ohio on Marble Lane.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] Some notable names for the game in languages other than English include Chinese: 跳皮筋; pinyin: *tiàopíjīn*, Japanese: "Rubber Jumping" (ゴムとび, *gomutobi*), German: **gummitwist**, and French: "jeu de l elastique".
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] The game is typically played by three or more players using a string of rubber bands that has been tied into a circle, usually at least six feet long ("approximately 2 feet in diameter"), or an elastic rope.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] Two of the participants (the holders) face each other several feet apart, and position the string around their ankles so that it is taut.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] The third player (the jumper) stands between the two sides of the rope and must accomplish a series of increasingly difficult moves without making an error.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] The position of the string is raised as the jumper moves through the levels, from ankle to waist height and higher.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] The game begins with choosing the jump pattern to follow and with the holders holding the rubberband around their ankles.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] There are many jump patterns and most are accompanied by a song.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] This is sometimes called the "first-level".
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] The jumper tries to complete the chosen pattern.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] If the moves are completed successfully, then the rope is moved farther up and the series is repeated.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] When the rope gets too high for a normal person to jump over it, the player then kneels and uses his or her hands instead.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] Some people just stop the game at this point, as the game is much easier when using hands.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] If the jumper makes a mistake, players rotate their positions and the next player becomes the jumper.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] Once the player is finished, that person switches with one of the other people, and so on, until everyone has been able to play.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] The moves involve jumping and repositioning the feet in some manner.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] Some of the more common moves are jumping so that both feet land outside the rope, both are inside the rope, one is inside and one is outside, or both are on top of the rope.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] These moves are called "out" (it may be thought of as "straddling".), "in", "side", and "on" respectively, which the two other participants chant as the player executes them.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] Some other, less common, moves involve manipulating the rope.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] A "pull" is when the jumper carries a side of the rope with one's foot or feet, generally crossing it over the other side.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] Crossing the ropes with one's legs in between them is "diamonds".
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] One of these moves, called "scissors", is executed by starting with both feet outside the rope and then crossing the legs, with the ropes in tow, so that a formation resembling a pair of scissors is formed.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] There are many variations of the game that are played.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] Sometimes the rope is crisscrossed so that it makes an X, and the player must move his or her feet into different sections of the X in some pattern.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] Instead of simply raising the rope, some players create a procession of "levels", similar to a video game, that the player must complete before winning the game.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] When a player returns to jumping, they continue the game from the last uncompleted level.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] The player that first completes the levels (usually five to nine, up to neck height) wins the game.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] These levels often have specific names, such as the "roller coaster," which is a crisscrossed rope that is higher at one end than the other.
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] There is a pattern known as "American" and one known as "the Name Game".
[src:chinese-jump-rope/chinese-jump-rope] Cinderella, dressed in yella (yellow) went upstairs to kiss a fella (fellow) she made a mistake and kissed a snake how many doctors did it take? one, two, three, four...
